name: Wisconsin Department of Revenue v. William Wrigley, Jr., Company
Lee v. Weisman
question: Does the inclusion of clergy who offer prayers at official public school ceremonies violate the Establishment Clause of the First Amendment?
description: A case in which the Court held that a Rhode Island public school bringing in a rabbi to offer prayers at a graduation ceremony violated the First Amendment.

name: Immigration and Naturalization Serv ice v. National Center for Immigrants' Rights
Franklin v. Massachusetts
question: Did the Secretary of Commerce's decision to apportion oversees personnel of the Department of Defense to their "homes of record" for census purposes meet the constitutional requirement of a census counting the number of people "in each State," or was the procedure "arbitrary and capricious" under the Administrative Procedure Act?

name: Nordlinger v. Hahn
question: Does Article XIIIA's "acquisition value provision," which created a dramatic disparity in the property taxes paid by long-term property owners as compared with new property owners, violate the Fourteenth Amendment's Equal Protection Clause by discriminating against new property owners?

name: Wooddell v. International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, Local 71
Rufo v. Inmates of Suffolk County Jail
question: Does the court require a grievous wrong evoked by new and unforeseen change of facts in order to modify a consented decree?
description: A case in which the Court held that the court does not require a grievous wrong evoked by new and unforeseen change of facts in order to modify a consented decree.

name: Morales v. Trans World Airlines, Inc.
question: Does the Airline Deregulation Act of 1978 prevent states from prohibiting deceptive airline fare advertisements through enforcement of their general consumer protection statuses?
description: A case in which the Court held that the Airline Deregulation Act of 1978 prevents states from prohibiting deceptive airline fare advertisements through enforcement of their general consumer protection statuses.

name: Planned Parenthood of Southeastern Pennsylvania v. Casey
question: Can a state require women who want an abortion to obtain informed consent, wait 24 hours, if married, notify their husbands, and, if minors, obtain parental consent, without violating their right to abortion as guaranteed by Roe v. Wade?
description: A case in which the Court introduced a new standard of determining the validity of abortion laws by asking if the restrictions place any "undue burden" on the mother attempting to abort the fetus. If the restriction is found to do so, it is invalid.

name: United States v. Fordice
question: Has Mississippi met its affirmative duty under the Fourteenth Amendment's Equal Protection Clause to dismantle its prior dual university system?

name: Lechmere, Inc. v. National Labor Relations Board
question: May nonemployee union organizers trespass on private property to solicit union support?

name: Hilton v. South Carolina Public Railways Commission
Fort Gratiot Sanitary Landfill, Inc. v. Michigan Department of Nat. Resources
United States Department of State v. Ray
United States v. Thompson/Center Arms Company
Cipollone v. Liggett Group, Inc.
question: Do federally mandated cigarette warnings pre-empt the Cipollones' common law claims against cigarette manufacturers?

name: United States v. Nordic Village, Inc.
Lujan v. Defenders of Wildlife
question: Do the respondents have standing to sue?

name: Robertson v. Seattle Audubon Society
question: Does § 318 of the Department of the Interior and Related Agencies Appropriations Act, violate Article III of the U.S. Constitution?

name: Gade v. National Solid Wastes Management Association
Riggins v. Nevada
question: Does the forced administration of antipsychotic drugs during trial violate the Sixth and Fourteenth Amendments?

name: Two Pesos, Inc. v. Taco Cabana, Inc.
question: Is proof of a secondary meaning required to show that trade dress is inherently distinctive and protected by the Lanham Act?

name: Quill Corporation v. North Dakota
question: 1) Had Bellas Hess become obsolete? 2) Was North Dakota's imposition of a use tax upon the merchandise of the Quill Corporation in compliance with the Due Process Clause and the Commerce Clause?

name: New York v. United States
question: Does the Low-Level Waste Act violate the Tenth Amendment and the "guarantee clause" of Article Four?

name: Kraft General Foods, Inc. v. Iowa Department of Revenue & Finance
Allied-Signal, Inc. v. Director, Division of Taxation
Immigration and Naturalization Service v. Elias-Zacarias
International Society for Krishna Consciousness, Inc. v. Lee
question: Does the regulation violate the First Amendment free speech clause?

name: Collins v. City of Harker Heights
Presley v. Etowah County Commission
question: Did the alterations imposed by the Etowah County Commission and the Russell County Commission regarding the scope of commissioner authority constitute changes "with respect to voting" according to section 5 of the Voting Rights Act of 1965?

name: Burson v. Freeman
question: Did Tennessee's 100-foot limit violate the First Amendment's freedom of speech?

name: Burlington Northern Railroad Company v. Ford
Federal Trade Commission v. Ticor Title Insurance Company
Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System of the United States v. MCorp Financial, Inc.
National Railroad Passenger Corporation v. Boston & Maine Corporation
question: Was the Interstate Commerce Commission's decision to permit Amtrak to seize the property of B & M Railroad under the Rail Passenger Service Act of 1970 reasonable?

name: Immigration and Naturalization Service v. Doherty
Georgia v. McCollum
question: Does the Equal Protection Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment of the United States Constitution prohibit a criminal defendant's use of peremptory challenges to discriminate against potential jurors on the basis of race?

name: Suter v. Artist M.
question: Does the Adoption Assistance and Child Welfare Act of 1980 create a "right" for the purposes of 42 U.S.C. 1983, allowing children affected by a state's adoption program to bring a private suit against its administrators?

name: Morgan v. Illinois
question: Do the Due Process Clause of the Fourteenth Amendment and the Sixth Amendment's impartial jury requirement bar a state from refusing to ask whether a potential juror would automatically vote to impose the death penalty upon a defendant convicted of a capital offense?

name: Hudson v. McMillian
question: Must an inmate alleging that his Eighth Amendment right to be free from cruel and unusual punishment has been violated by the excessive use of force demonstrate "significant injury" to prevail on his claim?

name: Bray v. Alexandria Women's Health Clinic
question: Did anti-abortion protesters who obstructed access to Washington, D.C. abortion clinics violate 42 U.S.C. 1985(3) by conspiring to deny women their "right to abortion" or right to interstate travel?

name: Jacobson v. United States
question: Did the prosecution against Jacobson prove, beyond a reasonable doubt, that agencies of the United States Government did not incite his violation of the Child Protection Act?

name: Estate of Cowart v. Nicklos Drilling Company
Eastman Kodak Company v. Image Technical Services., Inc.
Holmes v. Securities Investor Protection Corporation
Republic of Argentina v. Weltover, Inc.
question: Was the Republic of Argentina's default on certain bonds an act taken "in connection with a commercial activity" that had a "direct effect in the United States" so as to subject Argentina to suit in an American court under the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act of 1976?

name: County of Yakima v. Confederated Tribes & Bands of Yakima Indian Nation
White v. Illinois
question: Does the Confrontation Clause of the Sixth Amendment require either that the prosecution produce a declarant at trial or show that the declarant is unavailable before admitting his or her out-of-court statements under the “spontaneous declaration” and “medical examination” exceptions to the hearsay rule?
description: A case in which the Court held that the Confrontation Clause does not require that a declarant be produced at trial or found unavailable before his out-of-court statements may be admitted into evidence.

name: INDOPCO, Inc. v. Commissioner of Internal Revenue
United States v. R. L. C.
American National Red Cross v. S.G.
question: Does the "sue and be sued" provision in the Red Cross' charter confer original jurisdiction on federal courts over all cases to which the Red Cross is a party?

name: United States Department of Commerce v. Montana
Ardestani v. Immigration and Naturalization Service
Lucas v. South Carolina Coast Council
question: Does the construction ban depriving Lucas of all economically viable use of his property amount to a "taking" calling for "just compensation" under the Fifth and Fourteenth Amendments?

name: United States Department of Energy v. Ohio
Freeman v. Pitts
question: 1) Is a district court permitted to withdraw supervision of a school system that is under a court-ordered desegregation decree in the areas in which the school system complies with its decree if it does not comply in every area? 2) In the case of the DCSS, was the Court of Appeals correct in reversing the District Court's decision to withdraw supervision incrementally?

name: Lee v. International Society for Krishna Consciousness, Inc.
question: Does the regulation banning the distribution of literature at airports violate the free speech and free exercise clauses of the First Amendment?

name: Gomez v. United States District Court for the Northern District of California
question: Should the order staying Harris’ execution be vacated?
description: A case in which the Court vacated the stay of execution because Harris’s decision to wait so long to raise his cruel and unusual punishment claim represented an “obvious attempt” to manipulate the judicial process.

name: R.A.V. v. City of St. Paul
question: Is the ordinance overly broad and impermissibly content-based in violation of the First Amendment free speech clause?
description: A case in which the Court found a Minnesota ordinance violated the First Amendment because the ordinance was overly broad in the content-based speech it prohibited.

name: Nationwide Mutual Insurance Company v. Darden
Simon & Schuster, Inc. v. Members of New York State Crime Victims Board
question: Did the Son of Sam law violate the free speech clause of the First Amendment?

name: Chemical Waste Management, Inc. v. Hunt
Forsyth County v. Nationalist Movement
question: Does an ordinance that permits a government administrator to vary the fee for assembling or parading to reflect the estimated cost of maintaining public order violate the free speech guarantees under the First and Fourteenth Amendments?
description: A case in which the Court that an ordinance that permits a government administrator to vary the fee for assembling or parading to reflect the estimated cost of maintaining public order violated the free-speech guarantees under the First and Fourteenth Amendments.

name: Franklin v. Gwinnett County Public Schools
question: Does Title IX allow recovery of monetary damages?

name: Doggett v. United States
question:
Should a mandatory requirement of actual prejudice be imposed in order for the accused to prevail on a claim that his right to a speedy trial has been violated?

Has Moore v. Arizona, which holds that an affirmative demonstration of prejudice is not required, been reversed?
